08149nam a22010935i 9783110199093DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20082007gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831101990937 a10.1515/97831101990932doi  a(DE-B1597)33866  a(OCoLC)979731128  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLAN0090002bisacsh00aFocus Strategies in African Languages :bThe Interaction of Focus and Grammar in Niger-Congo and Afro-Asiatic /ced. by Enoch Oladé Aboh, Katharina Hartmann, Malte Zimmermann. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2008] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (324 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTrends in Linguistics. Studies and Monographs [TiLSM] ,x1861-4302 ;v19100tI-IV -- tContents -- tFocus and grammar: The contribution of African -- tlanguages -- tPart I. Focus and prosody -- tNuclear stress in eastern Benue-Kwa -- t(Niger-Congo) -- tInvestigating prosodic focus marking in Northern -- tSotho -- tPart II. Information structure and word -- torder -- tPreverbal objects and information structure in -- tBenue-Congo -- tFocus strategies and the incremental development of -- tsemantic representations: Evidence from Bantu -- tPart III. Ex-situ and in-situ strategies of focus -- tmarking -- tEx-situ focus in Kikuyu -- tFocus in the Force-Fin system: Information -- tstructure in Cushitic languages -- tCoptic relative tenses: The profile of a -- tmorpho-syntactic flagging device -- tPart IV. The inventory of focus marking -- tdevices -- tIdentificational operation as a focus strategy in -- tByali -- tExhaustivity marking in Hausa: A reanalysis of the -- tparticle nee/cee -- tPart V. Focus and related constructions -- tNarrative focus strategies in Gur and Kwa -- tFocused versus non-focused wh-phrases -- t315-3260 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOver the last two decades, focus has become a prominent topic in major fields in linguistic research (syntax, semantics, phonology). Focus Strategies in African Languages contributes to the ongoing discussion of focus by investigating focus-related phenomena in a range of African languages, most of which have been under-represented in the theoretical literature on focus. The articles in the volume look at focus strategies in Niger-Congo and Afro-Asiatic languages from several theoretical and methodological perspectives, ranging from detailed generative analysis to careful typological generalization across languages. Their common aim is to deepen our understanding of whether and how the information-structural category of focus is represented and marked in natural language. Topics investigated are, among others, the relation of focus and prosody, the effects of information structure on word order, ex situ versus in situ strategies of focus marking, the inventory of focus marking devices, focus and related constructions, focus-sensitive particles. The present inquiry into the focus systems of African languages has repercussions on existing theories of focus. It reveals new focus strategies as well as fine-tuned focus distinctions that are not discussed in the theoretical literature, which is almost exclusively based on well-documented intonation languages.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aAfroasiatic languagesxGrammar. 0aFocus (Linguistics). 0aNiger-Congo languagesxGrammar. 4aAfrika /Sprache. 4aPragmatik (Sprache). 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aAfrican languages.  apragmatics.1 aAboh, Enoch Oladé, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAboh, Enoch Oladé, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFiedler, Ines, econtributor.4ct